'''Nyatoh''' is a trade name for wood of a number of [[hardwood]] species of the genera ''[[Palaquium]]'' and ''[[Payena]]'' growing in [[rainforest]] environments in [[southeast Asia]], especially in [[Indonesia]] and the [[Philippines]].<ref name=Wood>{{cite web|title=Nyatoh|url=http://www.wood-database.com/lumber-identification/hardwoods/nyatoh/|website=The Wood Database|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> Nyatoh wood is reddish and most species are easy to work with and takes to stain and polish well. It has a tight [[wood grain|straight grain]] that resembles [[cherry wood]]. The surface is dark brown/red in color.<ref>{{cite book | author = Agus Sulistyo BUDI | editor = Andreas Schulte, Dieter Hans-Friedrich Schöne | title = Dipterocarp forest ecosystems: towards sustainable management | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oHNzvs02F5wC | accessdate = 2009-12-05 | year = 1996 | publisher = World Scientific | location = Singapore | isbn =978-981-02-2729-6 | pages = 591–601 | chapter = Properties and Utilization of Sapotaceous Timber from Dipterocarp Forests }}</ref>
== Sustainability == Nyatoh is generally perceived as a [[sustainability|sustainable resource]]. However, several species within the related [[genera]] of ''Palaquium'' and ''Payena'', and some ''Palaquium'' species, are on the [[IUCN Red List]] due to [[overexploitation]] and alarming reductions in their [[habitat]]s.<ref name=Wood />
The harvesting and sales of nyatoh has been criticized by some environmental groups, who have won agreements in the United States to not resell the wood from various furniture and home-improvement chains.<ref name="Vasil2009">{{cite book|last=Vasil|first=Adria|authorlink=Adria Vasil|title=Ecoholic Home: The Greenest, Cleanest and Most Energy-Efficient Information Under One (Canadian) Roof|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o2Hp88Q4pI0C&pg=PA178|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=2009-10-27|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=9780307357144|pages=178–}}</ref><ref name="Stanford2012">{{cite book|last=Stanford|first=Craig B.|title=Planet Without Apes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m3xqVaQaN54C&pg=PA43|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=2012-11-05|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674067882|pages=43–}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|quote=The result is that the company has stopped using the tropical wood nyatoh " because ...|title=Crate and Barrel goes "Green"|date=April 1, 2006|page=E4|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CS&s_site=thestate&p_multi=CS&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=110C88CFAD6402A8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=10 January 2013}}</ref>
